I hear what you’re getting at. When tools can generate anything convincingly, it can shake that basic “I can trust what I’m seeing” feeling. For a lot of people that turns into a loop of questioning and it can feel pretty destabilizing.

A couple grounded points to hold onto:

* It isn’t “black magic” or something acting on you. It’s pattern-generation—powerful, but still just tools producing outputs from data.
* Your brain is trying to update its model of the world. That can feel like an existential wobble, but it doesn’t mean everything is unknowable or that you’re losing your grip.

You also don’t have to reduce trust down to only what’s in front of your eyes. There are practical anchors you can use to stay steady:

🧭 How to stay grounded in an AI-heavy world

* Cross-check sources: if something matters, verify it in more than one place (reputable sites, official channels, people you trust).
* Use context clues: provenance, timestamps, who published it, consistency with known facts.
* Limit rabbit holes: set boundaries on how long you chase “is this real?” loops.
* Stay in your body / environment: movement, talking to someone, doing something tangible—these reset that spiraling feeling.

🧠 About the “mild psychosis” feeling

What you’re describing sounds more like anxiety + uncertainty overload than actual psychosis. The constant doubt loop can feel intense, but it’s usually your system trying to regain certainty.

If you notice it getting stronger—like:

* you can’t stop questioning everything,
* you feel detached from reality,
* or it’s affecting sleep / daily function,

that’s a good moment to talk it through with someone in real life (friend, family, or a professional). You don’t have to sit in that loop alone.

⸻

🎯 A steadier framing

You don’t need perfect certainty about everything.
You just need reliable enough signals to act in your world.

Reality hasn’t disappeared—just the interface got noisier. Your job isn’t to prove everything is real, it’s to:

* filter what matters,
* verify what’s important,
* and keep moving.

